Why do the -punk genres always come with these thick manuals about "doing it right"? I always find this obsession with purity laughable, considering the origins and nature of Cyberpunk. It's a wish fulfillment genre based around (the idea of) a subculture that takes the rules with a grain of salt in the first place. And finally, it's pretty much a dead nostalgia genre. It already happened. Except the hackers are the exact opposite of cool, the corporations hid their wrongdoing with PR instead of oppression, and the punks all went legit and support the system.

The stark reality is that the sort of urban mercenary type deal you see in Cyberpunk can really only happen with the approval of the state.

Cyberpunk is based around a series of very narrow tropes and ideas, that are often defended by some very narrow-minded people. Any serious treatment of the subject matter wouldn't really be Cyberpunk anymore. Not as we know it, anyway. The genre is mired in its 80's roots.

On the plus side, that does mean that today is the perfect time to return to Cyberpunk and really dial its tropes up to 11. And that's also the best way to subvert the genre itself, so that could be fun. A good way to comment on the transient nature of the genre is to make it perfectly clear that it's not actually set in a future of our world, as such, but an imagined future. A future where genetic meddling is still a long way off, where Soviet Russia still looms menacingly on the border of the civilized world, and where getting an industrial-type steel arm (and spine reinforcements!) still sounds like a better idea than a sleek, lightweight carbon model. Because MRI scans don't exist, either.

A crapsack 80's vision of the future, trapped in amber, that no-one will actually want to live in no matter how much they imagine themselves to be big damn heroes.
